Other features are his command of Virgilian diction¹‚ and of Classical prose rhythm2 especially noticeable in the clausulae of his paragraphS. A test of a different kind is to be found in a study of the quotations, which conform to the type represented by the Old Latin versions (based on the Septuagint), rather than to the Hebrew text as it was afterwards rendered in the Vulgate3.
